Chapter 1
Colun
Italianan time, 4:30 AM. Colun hated getting up so early. Mainly because he was responsible for waking up the rest of his squad. He quietly got out of bed, put on his combat suit, strapped on his assault vest, gathered his belongings from the storage cabinet, and carefully picked up a particularly small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his waistbelt. The helmet was equipped with all necessary gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other required items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he silently left the barracks, his boots making a creaking sound on the muddy and icy ground.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a light puff, then opened the door. In the past week, he had to use all his wits just to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm, as it didn't ring half the time and all he could hear through the speaker was a faint hissing sound.
"Are you going to wake them up?" Colun turned around and saw Lieutenant Nemich approaching.
"Yes." Colun replied.
"What method are you planning to use this time?"
Before Colun could reply, the door opened, and Harris, Crees, and several others rushed out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Crees said.
"What woke you all up?" Colun asked.
"First, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use to wake everyone up. Second, the first one up gets to enjoy breakfast first," a soldier named Ravik replied. "You know how terrible those breakfasts are."
"Right, Ravik," Colun said. He reached out and pressed the switch. Instantly, a piercing alarm blared through the barracks. He heard someone shouting inside, accompanied by a flurry of hurried footsteps.
"Good heavens, Valterri," Lieutenant Nemich said. "I thought they should have learned to get up with you by now."
"Brothers from my boot camp did it," Colun said, pointing at Harris, Crees, and Ravik. "But to be fair, their squad leader and platoon sergeant know to get up before their soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the squad ran out, all dressed and ready. Some new recruits looked groggy, while others appeared extremely annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Colun said cheerfully.
"Frankly, sir, why are you using that method to wake us up?" a junior sergeant asked.
"Because those ordinary alarms are just trash, and Daybreak never sleeps in." Colun said.
"Take your personal items," Colun continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the squad, he was responsible for assisting Captain Bolatin Xiao in supervising and leading the squad. "We won't be coming back. I give you and your squad members fifteen minutes to do the final check and bring the rations needed for today."
Members of Exodus Squad quickly dispersed. They were part of the Second Army's Second Assault Regiment. Before the merger, they were originally two independent squads, Cohort and Dagger. This was a elite squad, and Colun felt复杂的感情交织在一起 when he was promoted to lieutenant for various reasons.
Colun walked side by side with First Rank Officer Nemich on the brightly lit path within the base, where the lights on both sides were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, helping them avoid detection by enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak had begun employing the "Martlet" tactic in both the air and on the ground.
"New day, Hellbreakers' new mission," Nemich said with a dry laugh. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"At an advance base outside Ianlos. We were sent to support the ground offensive." Colun said, taking a puff of smoke. He somewhat blamed Crees for getting him hooked on cigarettes, but thinking about the past year filled with countless battles, he let it go and said nothing.
"Really bad. The front lines are under heavy attack," Nemich said softly. "All the news here is about 'supporting the war, aiding the Kurgan front.' Why not help the Howlan front once?"
"Right on, brother." Colun said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll go with the first tank platoon; we won't have to walk. Lieutenant Shao should be there."
"Lieutenant Shao is letting us ride along?" Nemich asked, sounding surprised.
"Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not someone you'd really dislike either."
Colun raised his thumb and index finger, pressing the microphone against his throat, and shifted his backpack onto his back. "All units of Exodus Squad, assemble at the west vehicle depot after completing your missions. We will depart with the first tank platoon at 05:00."
Every few seconds, he received replies from his platoon leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Crees, and Ravik were lower-ranking sergeants. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them had been good friends. Colun felt as if it had been a long time since he knew them, even though less than two years had passed. They were all platoon leaders, but after the former second platoon leader was retired due to injury from Daybreak snipers a week ago, Crees began leading the second platoon.
Walking to the vehicle depot, Colun and Nemich's eyes fell upon approximately eight Kronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were scurrying about, ensuring their war machines were in top condition. Colun quickly spotted Lieutenant Bolatin Xiao among the crowd, who was engaged in conversation with the tank platoon commander. As they approached, Lieutenant Xiao glanced at them and came forward, his usually emotionless face showing no reaction.
"Second Lieutenant Nemich... Lieutenant Valterri..." he said, Colun slowed his steps, and Lieutenant Xiao looked at Colun's holster, then raised his head. "Should the company be ready by now?"
